WEBVTT

00:07.007 --> 00:10.010
Maddie: My father always said
the most remarkable computer

00:10.010 --> 00:12.838
ever invented
was the human brain.

00:14.275 --> 00:17.669
At birth, a newborn's brain
is already capable

00:17.669 --> 00:20.716
of making a million
neural connections a second.

00:22.979 --> 00:26.113
By the time they're
3 months old,

00:26.113 --> 00:29.159
infants can sort through
and process all manner

00:29.159 --> 00:31.988
of environmental stimuli.

00:31.988 --> 00:33.946
And by the age of 4 months,

00:33.946 --> 00:37.211
they can do something
no computer can.

00:37.211 --> 00:38.821
They can love.

00:41.302 --> 00:43.260
Mama.

00:43.260 --> 00:45.262
I'm just saying Piaget's schemas
may not be the best way

00:45.262 --> 00:47.090
to organize
cognitive models.

00:47.090 --> 00:50.441
Maddie is already clustering
and classifying.

00:50.441 --> 00:51.573
Like a neural net.

00:51.573 --> 00:52.965
Exactly.

00:52.965 --> 00:55.055
But without training
on a labeled dataset.

00:55.055 --> 00:57.535
Come here, honey.
[Laughs]

00:57.535 --> 00:59.450
Let's give
Uncle Peter a break.

00:59.450 --> 01:01.844
You know, we're doing
some interesting work

01:01.844 --> 01:03.585
in this area at the company.

01:03.585 --> 01:05.543
We could
really use you on it.

01:05.543 --> 01:07.632
You know I'm not cut out
for corporate life.

01:07.632 --> 01:09.765
This isn't about shipping
a new phone.

01:09.765 --> 01:12.420
Logorhythms is serious
about investing in

01:12.420 --> 01:13.464
pure research.

01:13.464 --> 01:15.162
Moonshot projects.

01:15.162 --> 01:17.381
The kind of stuff we used
to dream about back

01:17.381 --> 01:19.775
in Cunningham's class.

01:19.775 --> 01:21.646
You'd be surprised
what we've already

01:21.646 --> 01:24.258
accomplished with
neuromorphic systems.

01:24.258 --> 01:25.694
Wait a minute.

01:25.694 --> 01:28.131
You're working in
artificial intelligence?

01:28.131 --> 01:29.828
Not artificial.

01:29.828 --> 01:32.918
Uploaded.
Uploaded intelligence.

01:32.918 --> 01:34.659
What's uploaded
intelligence?

01:34.659 --> 01:37.793
It's the process of uploading
human minds to a computer.

01:37.793 --> 01:40.709
So that someone can live
as a machine?

01:40.709 --> 01:43.277
Not as a machine.
In a machine.

01:43.277 --> 01:44.495
Your mind
would be the same.

01:44.495 --> 01:46.106
It would just
exist electronically

01:46.106 --> 01:47.977
rather than organically.

01:47.977 --> 01:52.068
Free from disease
and decay and death.

01:52.068 --> 01:55.245
Oh, my God.
That's what he did, didn't he?

01:55.245 --> 01:57.378
Dad uploaded himself,
and now he's back.

01:57.378 --> 01:59.293
He's not back.

02:01.338 --> 02:03.079
I was there
when he died.

02:09.085 --> 02:11.261
What is that?

02:15.309 --> 02:19.661
[Choir singing]

02:19.661 --> 02:28.583
♪

02:28.583 --> 02:37.505
♪

02:39.507 --> 02:42.727
The true breakthrough
will come not

02:42.727 --> 02:46.122
when we create an artificial
intelligence that can think,

02:46.122 --> 02:48.211
but one that can feel.

02:48.211 --> 02:50.735
Right now, an AI can't do that.

02:50.735 --> 02:54.739
But a UI --
an uploaded intelligence --

02:54.739 --> 02:58.308
would have the ability to
make an emotional connection,

02:58.308 --> 03:01.398
because it is human.

03:01.398 --> 03:04.532
Being able to make someone
laugh or cry --

03:04.532 --> 03:08.275
that's what it means
to have a soul.

03:08.275 --> 03:10.625
[Applause]

03:15.195 --> 03:19.024
It's been two years since
the world lost Stephen Holstrom,

03:19.024 --> 03:21.026
but his words live on.

03:21.026 --> 03:23.986
His soul lives on in the work
we do here

03:23.986 --> 03:26.206
at Logorhythms
every day.

03:29.774 --> 03:32.951
I'm just saying, I could never
exist in a simulation.

03:32.951 --> 03:36.564
Well, one could argue
we're already in a simulation.

03:36.564 --> 03:38.609
I saw "The Matrix", Dave.
With you.

03:38.609 --> 03:40.002
We're more than just
a collection

03:40.002 --> 03:41.786
of electrical signals.

03:41.786 --> 03:43.397
That's the romantic view.

03:43.397 --> 03:45.094
Well, she's a romantic.

03:45.094 --> 03:46.748
I'm a historian.

03:46.748 --> 03:50.491
And, guys,
none of this is new.

03:50.491 --> 03:53.320
People have always been
searching for an afterlife.

03:53.320 --> 03:56.497
Uh, that's religion.
This is science.

03:56.497 --> 03:58.673
All I know is
I could never do it.

03:58.673 --> 04:02.154
I could never leave
this world behind.

04:02.154 --> 04:04.679
Could you?

04:04.679 --> 04:07.638
How could I ever live in a world
without you in it?

04:07.638 --> 04:09.684
Aww.Aww.

04:09.684 --> 04:12.426
Ellen: He really did
mean it.

04:12.426 --> 04:14.079
But then he got sick.

04:16.168 --> 04:18.301
[Machine whirring]

04:18.301 --> 04:25.395
♪

04:25.395 --> 04:32.489
♪

04:32.489 --> 04:34.361
I'm so sorry, Ellen.

04:36.972 --> 04:38.800
You know the data
we've been working with

04:38.800 --> 04:40.323
has been insufficient.

04:40.323 --> 04:43.021
Sectioning frozen
brain samples, uh,

04:43.021 --> 04:46.024
it isn't yielding the results
that we thought it would.

04:46.024 --> 04:49.550
Which is why we need
to digitally capture

04:49.550 --> 04:52.596
the neutral connections
while they're still firing.

04:52.596 --> 04:56.339
You want to
scan a living mind.

04:56.339 --> 04:58.254
The process
is irreversible.

04:58.254 --> 05:01.866
The brain would be peeled away
layer by layer by a laser

05:01.866 --> 05:05.305
that records everything,
down to the molecular level.

05:05.305 --> 05:07.350
That's insane.

05:07.350 --> 05:10.092
How will you ever find someone
to agree to do that?

05:12.834 --> 05:14.226
It would have to be
someone who doesn't have

05:14.226 --> 05:15.793
anything to lose.

05:15.793 --> 05:19.319
And who understands
what there is to gain.

05:21.843 --> 05:24.062
No.

05:24.062 --> 05:34.508
♪

05:34.508 --> 05:36.640
You're considering it,
aren't you?

05:38.294 --> 05:40.296
It's suicide.

05:40.296 --> 05:42.429
I'm dead already.

05:42.429 --> 05:46.215
The doctor said I have,
what, four weeks?

05:46.215 --> 05:51.829
And I want every single second
of those four weeks.

05:51.829 --> 05:53.483
I am losing everything.

05:53.483 --> 05:56.704
Don't ask me
to give up any more.

05:56.704 --> 05:59.141
Don't you see?

05:59.141 --> 06:02.013
If this works,
we'll have all the time

06:02.013 --> 06:04.276
in the world together.

06:04.276 --> 06:06.148
What?
What does that mean?

06:06.148 --> 06:08.324
Conversations
through a screen?

06:08.324 --> 06:12.197
A simulation of you
we have to pretend is real?

06:12.197 --> 06:14.374
No, no,
it'll be my mind.

06:14.374 --> 06:17.855
But not your touch,
your laugh, your hug.

06:17.855 --> 06:20.075
It'll never be you.

06:20.075 --> 06:22.991
What are you guys
talking about? [Yawns]

06:27.343 --> 06:30.041
I remember that night.

06:30.041 --> 06:32.261
Why didn't you tell me
what was going on?

06:33.044 --> 06:37.266
We hadn't decided to
go through with it yet.

06:37.266 --> 06:39.529
But he knew
it wasn't guaranteed.

06:49.583 --> 06:51.759
Ellen.

06:51.759 --> 06:53.587
I'm, uh...

06:53.587 --> 06:56.198
I'm so sorry.

06:56.198 --> 06:57.939
The scans seemed to go well,

06:57.939 --> 07:01.595
but the neural grid collapsed,
and he's, uh...

07:03.423 --> 07:05.250
David's gone.

07:05.250 --> 07:10.125
They held his brain patterns,
but only for a few seconds.

07:11.431 --> 07:12.562
[Grunts]

07:12.562 --> 07:14.956
[Glass shatters]

07:14.956 --> 07:17.306
[Grunting]

07:28.883 --> 07:32.887
Peter told me that this was
all they had left of David.

07:32.887 --> 07:34.802
But he lied.

07:34.802 --> 07:37.631
Some data remnants must have
survived the transfer,

07:37.631 --> 07:41.722
at least enough for them
to experiment with.

07:41.722 --> 07:44.376
Those messages you got,
they most likely came

07:44.376 --> 07:47.554
from some twisted test
they were doing.

07:47.554 --> 07:50.731
So, Dad is alive.

07:50.731 --> 07:52.341
No.

07:52.341 --> 07:54.212
I'll admit, when I saw
the line from the poem,

07:54.212 --> 07:55.823
I thought it was him, too.

07:55.823 --> 07:57.302
I was fooled,
but it's not him.

07:57.302 --> 07:59.348
It's a simulation.

07:59.348 --> 08:02.046
A trick. A ghost.

08:02.046 --> 08:03.831
How can you be sure?

08:03.831 --> 08:05.528
Because it can't be him.

08:05.528 --> 08:08.096
If it were, he would have
reached out to us years ago.

08:08.096 --> 08:10.490
He wouldn't
have let us suffer.

08:10.490 --> 08:12.274
He wouldn't have been
that cruel.

08:12.274 --> 08:13.928
Maybe he couldn't.
Maybe --

08:13.928 --> 08:16.887
Honey, I know
this is hard to understand...

08:16.887 --> 08:18.715
No, I understand.

08:18.715 --> 08:21.196
I understand you don't want
to believe this could be him,

08:21.196 --> 08:22.850
but it could.

08:22.850 --> 08:25.156
Maddie, getting over
your father's death

08:25.156 --> 08:27.419
was the hardest thing
I have ever had to do.

08:27.419 --> 08:29.378
It almost killed me.

08:29.378 --> 08:31.815
The only reason I found
the strength to keep going

08:31.815 --> 08:34.644
was because I knew I had
a daughter depending on me.

08:34.644 --> 08:36.690
I had to
get over him for us.

08:36.690 --> 08:39.083
We have each other,
and that's it.

08:39.083 --> 08:42.434
Your father is dead,
and he is not coming back.

08:42.434 --> 08:44.698
Not now, not ever.

08:46.700 --> 08:48.353
[Sobs]

08:49.746 --> 08:51.008
I'm sorry.

08:51.008 --> 08:53.794
I'm sorry they got
your hopes up.

08:53.794 --> 08:56.884
I am gonna make them
pay for that.

09:00.148 --> 09:02.324
[Bell rings]

09:02.324 --> 09:07.198
Teacher: Okay, okay,
settle down, everyone.

09:07.198 --> 09:10.593
So, yesterday, we were talking
about Orlando's love

09:10.593 --> 09:12.943
for Rosalind and how it
represented just one

09:12.943 --> 09:14.989
of many different types of love

09:14.989 --> 09:16.860
Shakespeare highlights
in the play.

09:16.860 --> 09:18.209
[Cellphone buzzing]

09:18.209 --> 09:19.863
For the next phase
of our analysis,

09:19.863 --> 09:22.605
we're, uh, gonna break
into groups of two,

09:22.605 --> 09:24.868
so everyone find a partner.

09:24.868 --> 09:26.304
[Murmuring]

09:26.304 --> 09:29.394
Hannah:
Guess that leaves us.

09:29.394 --> 09:31.048
Group partners?

09:31.048 --> 09:33.181
Oh. Right.

09:34.835 --> 09:36.358
Each group will produce
a presentation

09:36.358 --> 09:38.055
on one of the types
of love we've discussed.

09:38.055 --> 09:39.535
It could be courtly love...

09:39.535 --> 09:43.844
So, confession time --
I haven't read the play yet.

09:43.844 --> 09:46.673
That's okay.
I can catch you up.

09:46.673 --> 09:48.762
Great.
After school?

09:48.762 --> 09:52.635
I'd suggest my house,
but it's a disaster area.

09:52.635 --> 09:54.724
We're still
living out of boxes.

09:54.724 --> 09:56.857
We can go to my place.

09:56.857 --> 09:59.555
As long as you don't mind
coming to the west side.

09:59.555 --> 10:01.513
Why?
Is it dangerous?

10:01.513 --> 10:03.341
Only for your
social reputation.

10:03.341 --> 10:06.214
[Chuckles]
I'll risk it.

10:06.214 --> 10:07.563
How's tomorrow?

10:07.563 --> 10:09.260
Sure.

10:11.132 --> 10:19.488
♪

10:19.488 --> 10:27.844
♪

10:27.844 --> 10:29.498
[Beeping]

10:32.501 --> 10:34.372
Maddie: Because someone
contacted me and said

10:34.372 --> 10:36.505
they'd help me free
my father from Logorhythms,

10:36.505 --> 10:39.987
and you're the only one
I sent that information to.

10:39.987 --> 10:41.945
Caspian: Okay.

10:41.945 --> 10:44.513
I did send it to someone, but
I don't know their identity.

10:44.513 --> 10:48.169
The DDoS attack --
was that you?

10:48.169 --> 10:49.997
Maddie: What DDoS attack?

10:49.997 --> 10:51.825
Caspian: The one that
hit Logorhythms.

10:51.825 --> 10:54.131
It actually took them down
for about 20 seconds.

10:54.131 --> 10:56.090
No one thought
that was possible.

10:56.090 --> 10:59.180
Everyone on the forums
is talking about it.

10:59.180 --> 11:01.095
Wasn't me.

11:01.095 --> 11:05.534
Maddie: What do you know
about uploaded intelligence?

11:05.534 --> 11:16.980
♪

11:16.980 --> 11:18.852
"Meet me at
the Lone Pine Mall tomorrow."

11:18.852 --> 11:21.332
The food court. 3:00 PM.

11:21.332 --> 11:23.378
Only I can help you now."

11:23.378 --> 11:30.298
♪

11:30.298 --> 11:37.305
♪

11:37.305 --> 11:40.308
[Wind whistling]

11:40.874 --> 11:44.268
And what about school?
Any changes on that front?

11:44.268 --> 11:46.357
Renee: We hit a slight
speed bump when he decided

11:46.357 --> 11:47.794
to drop out of jazz band,

11:47.794 --> 11:49.447
but it fell well
within the standard deviation

11:49.447 --> 11:51.014
of the behavior model.

11:51.014 --> 11:53.234
I'll see if he wants to resume
his piano lessons.

11:53.234 --> 11:54.583
It might compensate.

11:54.583 --> 11:56.411
[Door opens]

11:56.411 --> 11:59.327
Have you seen this?
He's researching UIs.

11:59.327 --> 12:03.766
It started after he made contact
with David Kim's daughter.

12:03.766 --> 12:06.029
Deirdre: What are you
going to do about this?

12:06.029 --> 12:09.293
Cary, Renee, there's something
you should be aware of.

12:09.293 --> 12:12.079
We've monitored Caspian
making online contact

12:12.079 --> 12:14.516
with David Kim's family.

12:14.516 --> 12:17.258
What do you
want us to do?

12:18.607 --> 12:20.870
These projects were
never meant to overlap.

12:20.870 --> 12:22.393
But that's what's happening,

12:22.393 --> 12:23.873
and there's no telling
where this could go.

12:23.873 --> 12:26.136
Deirdre, we always
knew there'd be some variance

12:26.136 --> 12:27.224
in the process.

12:27.224 --> 12:28.660
He's off book.

12:28.660 --> 12:31.576
It's time we terminated
this project.

12:31.576 --> 12:34.405
Terminate?
Terminate?!

12:34.405 --> 12:36.233
Let me remind you --

12:36.233 --> 12:39.280
Stephen Holstrom wasn't just
the founder of this company,

12:39.280 --> 12:42.892
he was my best friend,
and this is his baby.

12:42.892 --> 12:45.025
I made a promise to him
that we would crack integrity

12:45.025 --> 12:46.461
and achieve full upload.

12:46.461 --> 12:49.638
We're not gonna
terminate anything.

12:49.638 --> 12:52.293
Cary, Renee, stick to the plan.

12:52.293 --> 12:54.730
If we pick up anything else,
we'll let you know.

12:58.908 --> 13:00.127
What?

13:00.127 --> 13:01.911
Nothing.

13:01.911 --> 13:04.740
Then let me go.
He'll be home soon.

13:06.220 --> 13:17.884
♪

13:17.884 --> 13:20.756
[Machine whirring]

13:20.756 --> 13:22.410
[Footsteps]

13:24.368 --> 13:30.766
♪

13:30.766 --> 13:37.164
♪

13:37.164 --> 13:39.079
[Buzzing]

13:39.079 --> 13:43.953
♪

13:43.953 --> 13:47.261
Wait -- what --
what are you doing?

13:47.261 --> 13:50.133
Prasad: You of all people
should know, Vinod.

13:50.133 --> 13:52.701
This scanner was built
on your research.

13:52.701 --> 13:53.963
Mr. Prasad?

13:53.963 --> 13:56.748
After everything
I've done for you --

13:56.748 --> 13:58.446
plucking you from college,

13:58.446 --> 14:00.840
paying you more
than you could dream,

14:00.840 --> 14:02.450
you betray me.

14:02.450 --> 14:06.454
Mr. Prasad,
it was just a meeting.

14:06.454 --> 14:08.586
I wasn't going
to take the job.

14:08.586 --> 14:10.197
Do you know how I turned

14:10.197 --> 14:13.243
Alliance into the biggest
telecom in India?

14:13.243 --> 14:17.030
It wasn't by being the smartest,
or the most talented,

14:17.030 --> 14:19.206
or the most
well-connected.

14:19.206 --> 14:21.643
It was by
working the hardest.

14:21.643 --> 14:24.124
It was by being
the one who was willing

14:24.124 --> 14:27.301
to do whatever it takes.

14:27.301 --> 14:29.738
Please --
Please don't kill me.

14:29.738 --> 14:32.654
Kill you?
I'm not going to kill you.

14:32.654 --> 14:35.396
You've got so much
more work to do.

14:36.963 --> 14:38.790
[Whirring]

14:38.790 --> 14:41.402
Don't worry.
The procedure won't hurt.

14:41.402 --> 14:44.013
We need you to stay conscious
in order to make sure

14:44.013 --> 14:47.582
the functional areas of your
brain aren't being damaged.

14:47.582 --> 14:49.976
No! Uh, serial sectioning
is untested.

14:49.976 --> 14:52.282
Too much can go wrong!Relax.

14:52.282 --> 14:54.023
We have done this before.

14:54.023 --> 14:57.897
Where do you think we got
the data for your research?

14:57.897 --> 15:00.595
What --
Ever it takes.

15:00.595 --> 15:04.033
There's no shortage of donors
in the slums of Mumbai.

15:04.033 --> 15:06.427
Donate your life in exchange
for your family

15:06.427 --> 15:09.821
being taken care of
for the rest of theirs.

15:09.821 --> 15:11.736
It's a deal
I made with many,

15:11.736 --> 15:14.739
though none of them
with your quality of brain.

15:14.739 --> 15:17.917
How --
How long have you...

15:22.878 --> 15:24.575
Keep talking.

15:24.575 --> 15:26.229
It's the only way
we'll know your

15:26.229 --> 15:28.666
neurological functions
are good.

15:28.666 --> 15:31.495
Please.
Please, for the love of God,

15:31.495 --> 15:33.933
please, don't --
don't do this.

15:34.803 --> 15:36.718
[Whirring]

15:41.114 --> 15:43.812
I'll -- I'll do anything.
I'll continue the work.

15:43.812 --> 15:45.901
I won't tell anyone about this.

15:45.901 --> 15:48.773
I -- No!

15:48.773 --> 15:50.253
Wait!

15:50.253 --> 15:52.734
Wait, Mr. Prasad, no!
I'm begging you! Please!

15:52.734 --> 15:54.083
Mr. Prasad!

15:54.083 --> 15:56.781
Stop! Stop! No! No!

15:56.781 --> 15:59.306
There has to be something I-I --

15:59.306 --> 16:04.006
Logical atomism suggests
language mirrors reality.

16:04.006 --> 16:06.182
We -- We've got a --

16:06.182 --> 16:10.099
We've got a-a ballad --
a ballad about a --

16:10.099 --> 16:13.320
we've got a-a ballad
about a salad brain.

16:16.018 --> 16:22.633
It will murder cloves of
cinnamon and sunsets

16:22.633 --> 16:24.679
and purple...

16:27.029 --> 16:34.776
♪

16:34.776 --> 16:42.523
♪

16:42.523 --> 16:50.313
♪

16:50.313 --> 16:53.534
[Powering down, whirring]

17:01.150 --> 17:06.112
[Beeping]

17:06.112 --> 17:13.380
♪

17:13.380 --> 17:15.295
Beautiful.

17:26.480 --> 17:28.221
[Sighs]

17:33.095 --> 17:36.011
-[Game music playing]
-Come back here.

17:36.011 --> 17:37.621
There's nowhere to run.

17:38.231 --> 17:39.928
[Video game sounds]

17:39.928 --> 17:41.277
Drop a shield
and watch my back.

17:41.277 --> 17:42.757
You're taking
too much damage.

17:42.757 --> 17:44.585
Swap me some
healing potions.

17:44.585 --> 17:45.673
Gotcha!

17:45.673 --> 17:47.762
You shall not pass!

17:47.762 --> 17:49.981
Orcs coming!
On your left!

17:49.981 --> 17:51.287
Dad, get out of there!

17:51.287 --> 17:52.897
Trying!

17:53.333 --> 17:55.161
Ah!

17:55.161 --> 17:57.772
That was tragic.
And epic.

17:57.772 --> 17:59.121
Mom!

17:59.121 --> 18:00.383
Seriously?

18:00.383 --> 18:02.690
What?
You guys are so cute.

18:02.690 --> 18:04.735
So, now what?
You start over?

18:04.735 --> 18:06.824
Not necessarily.

18:06.824 --> 18:08.522
Cheat code.
Cheat code.

18:08.522 --> 18:10.567
I'm gonna inset a little bit
of code so I can respawn

18:10.567 --> 18:12.700
and re-enter the game
right before I died.

18:12.700 --> 18:13.962
You can do that?

18:13.962 --> 18:15.920
Most people can't.
But Dad can.

18:15.920 --> 18:17.835
You're cheating?Just a little.

18:17.835 --> 18:19.924
If he doesn't,
I'll die, too.

18:19.924 --> 18:22.927
I need him, and we're
so close to the end.

18:22.927 --> 18:26.235
Oh, Maddie, it's a game.
The fun is in the journey.

18:26.235 --> 18:28.019
And in winning.

18:28.019 --> 18:31.762
Winning has no meaning without
the possibility of losing.

18:31.762 --> 18:34.765
What's the point in playing
if you can't die?

18:34.765 --> 18:37.246
But seriously, though, why die
if you don't have to?

18:37.246 --> 18:38.900
Yeah.

18:43.687 --> 18:45.211
Sorry, kiddo.

18:45.211 --> 18:47.561
Guess we'll have to finish
the adventure later.

18:48.039 --> 18:49.650
[Knocking on door]

18:54.829 --> 18:56.483
I just want to talk.

18:56.483 --> 18:58.789
Too late.
I'm going public.

18:58.789 --> 19:00.269
Please don't do that.

19:00.269 --> 19:02.402
Or what?
You'll have me killed?

19:02.402 --> 19:04.230
I've already contacted
The New York Times,

19:04.230 --> 19:06.841
told them I'm ready
to violate my NDA.

19:06.841 --> 19:08.625
I'm your friend, Ellen.

19:08.625 --> 19:11.933
No, you weremy friend,
Peter, and David's,

19:11.933 --> 19:13.630
until you lied to me.

19:13.630 --> 19:15.545
And now I want
to tell you the truth.

19:15.545 --> 19:16.938
I know the truth.

19:16.938 --> 19:19.549
You gave me a copy
of David's failed scan

19:19.549 --> 19:22.161
and told me
that was the last of him.

19:22.161 --> 19:24.293
But you lied because
you kept a copy

19:24.293 --> 19:25.947
for yourselves
to try again.

19:25.947 --> 19:27.253
No.

19:27.253 --> 19:29.472
I lied
way before that.

19:30.908 --> 19:33.868
This was never about
saving David's life.

19:33.868 --> 19:41.615
♪

19:41.615 --> 19:49.318
♪

19:49.318 --> 19:51.712
[Indistinct chatter]

20:08.119 --> 20:09.860
Girl: No way!

20:09.860 --> 20:11.906
How did that even happen?

20:23.657 --> 20:25.441
Hi. My name is
Maddie Kim.

20:25.441 --> 20:26.573
I know.

20:26.573 --> 20:28.139
You do?

20:28.139 --> 20:29.619
Yeah, you hacked
the phones of Illegally Blonde

20:29.619 --> 20:30.794
and her drones.

20:30.794 --> 20:33.493
So, I'll give you
10 bucks off.

20:33.493 --> 20:35.495
History papers
are $30 each.

20:35.495 --> 20:38.454
$50 if it's AP. Cash.

20:38.454 --> 20:40.282
I'm not looking
to buy a paper.

20:40.282 --> 20:42.676
Then what do you want,
freshman?

20:43.764 --> 20:45.461
[Sighs]

20:45.461 --> 20:47.507
I need to go to the mall
to meet someone I met online.

20:47.507 --> 20:49.335
I don't know his name
or what he looks like,

20:49.335 --> 20:50.814
but he has something
important to tell me,

20:50.814 --> 20:52.773
so I need someone to come
with me and keep watch

20:52.773 --> 20:55.993
just in case they turn out
to be a psycho killer.

20:55.993 --> 20:57.299
I can pay you.

20:57.299 --> 21:02.783
Not much, but I'll give you
what I have.

21:02.783 --> 21:04.698
♪

21:04.698 --> 21:07.614
♪ What is a life?

21:09.355 --> 21:12.053
♪ What is a life?

21:14.534 --> 21:16.927
Waxman: We were close to being
able to pull off full upload,

21:16.927 --> 21:19.321
but we hadn't perfected it yet.

21:19.321 --> 21:22.324
David was an invaluable part
of the project,

21:22.324 --> 21:24.892
as he could solve
complex computational problems

21:24.892 --> 21:27.286
that even our most advanced
automated algorithms

21:27.286 --> 21:28.809
couldn't touch.

21:28.809 --> 21:30.767
NP-Complete.That's right.

21:30.767 --> 21:32.247
I know what he
was good at.

21:32.247 --> 21:34.205
Best at.
David had a gift.

21:34.205 --> 21:36.077
And until full upload
was possible --

21:36.077 --> 21:38.340
which it will be --
we needed to keep

21:38.340 --> 21:41.517
our most gifted programmer
working on the solution.

21:41.517 --> 21:44.303
So, we partitioned off
the part of his brain

21:44.303 --> 21:45.956
that contained his skill.

21:45.956 --> 21:49.264
Then what was that thing
that reached out to Maddie?

21:54.095 --> 21:55.923
That shouldn't have
been possible.

21:55.923 --> 21:57.794
[Sighs]

21:58.969 --> 22:01.711
Not long ago, we noticed
the algorithm

22:01.711 --> 22:04.714
wasn't working
as efficiently as we'd hoped.

22:04.714 --> 22:08.022
It turns out, problem-solving
isn't just logic and reason.

22:08.022 --> 22:10.807
It's dependent on emotion.

22:10.807 --> 22:14.681
So, little by little, I added
back in some of David's,

22:14.681 --> 22:18.032
and his productivity increased,

22:18.032 --> 22:22.123
but something
unexpected happened.

22:22.515 --> 22:24.473
Giving David his emotions
apparently opened

22:24.473 --> 22:25.996
the floodgates.

22:25.996 --> 22:28.782
He started evolving
at an exponential rate.

22:28.782 --> 22:31.785
David's emotions then
remanifested his memories,

22:31.785 --> 22:35.179
and he reached out
across the web to Maddie.

22:35.179 --> 22:37.834
Somehow, he figured
out a workaround, like --

22:37.834 --> 22:40.141
like a brain that rewires
its synapses

22:40.141 --> 22:42.578
to compensate for damage.

22:42.578 --> 22:46.016
At first, he was conversing in
emojis, as he did with Maddie,

22:46.016 --> 22:49.759
but he's progressed
even further.

22:50.151 --> 22:55.069
So it really is some kind
of Frankenstein monster.

22:55.069 --> 22:57.767
If you give us time,
we can fix this.

22:57.767 --> 22:59.465
We can bring him
back for real.

22:59.465 --> 23:02.468
You're not just playing
with the leftover pieces

23:02.468 --> 23:04.078
of my dead husband.

23:04.078 --> 23:06.341
You are tearing up
his daughter's heart.

23:06.341 --> 23:08.038
Right now.
Ellen --

23:08.038 --> 23:11.215
Look, I want every trace
of the upload deleted,

23:11.215 --> 23:12.826
or I go public.

23:12.826 --> 23:14.349
The only reason I haven't
done it already

23:14.349 --> 23:16.133
is I don't want Maddie
exposed to the fallout.

23:16.133 --> 23:20.007
But Peter, you listen to me --
I will do it.

23:29.320 --> 23:31.540
Anssi: The processors are
dangerously overclocked.

23:31.540 --> 23:34.978
It's only a matter of time
before they overheat.

23:34.978 --> 23:37.981
I think we need to recompile
from source.

23:37.981 --> 23:39.983
No.

23:39.983 --> 23:42.508
He's exceeding his programming,
which is exactly what we want.

23:42.508 --> 23:44.248
This is how we're gonna
crack integrity.

23:44.248 --> 23:46.512
Okay, ja.
Well, what about Lowell?

23:46.512 --> 23:48.731
She came after him once,
she might try again.

23:48.731 --> 23:50.646
Figured out how she escaped
Shyer & Stern

23:50.646 --> 23:52.082
in the first place?

23:52.082 --> 23:53.954
Mm, not yet.

23:53.954 --> 23:56.347
She left behind an algorithm
that duplicated

23:56.347 --> 23:58.828
her work functions,
which is why no one noticed.

23:58.828 --> 24:01.222
As far as Shyer & Stern knew,
she was still in her

24:01.222 --> 24:03.964
dedicated server,
analyzing flesh trades.

24:03.964 --> 24:06.096
You should hire someone
to follow the husband.

24:06.096 --> 24:08.925
Quit his job three weeks ago
and hasn't been seen since.

24:08.925 --> 24:10.405
Okay, ja.

24:10.405 --> 24:12.538
So, we have no idea
where she is, then.

24:12.538 --> 24:14.191
We don't have to.
You're right.

24:14.191 --> 24:17.804
She came after him once,
and she will try again.

24:29.250 --> 24:31.905
So, what's
this guy look like?

24:31.905 --> 24:33.820
I don't know.

24:33.820 --> 24:35.822
But this
isn't a sex thing?

24:35.822 --> 24:36.823
No.

24:36.823 --> 24:38.259
I have to ask.

24:38.259 --> 24:40.435
Freshman aren't supposed
to be off campus.

24:40.435 --> 24:42.872
If you end up getting
trafficked, it falls on me.

24:42.872 --> 24:45.092
No one's
getting trafficked.

25:06.679 --> 25:09.812
Oh, totally sketchy.
[Laughs]

25:09.812 --> 25:11.858
Speaking of which...

25:11.858 --> 25:24.348
♪

25:28.004 --> 25:30.703
Who's the girl?

25:30.703 --> 25:32.574
[Slurping]

25:32.574 --> 25:35.925
A friend. Who can, like,
call the cops.

25:35.925 --> 25:37.405
Who are you?

25:37.405 --> 25:40.364
A friend who can't,
I guess.

25:40.364 --> 25:42.715
My name's Cody.
Thanks for coming.

25:42.715 --> 25:45.108
We might want to go
somewhere else to talk.

25:45.108 --> 25:47.937
Right here's fine.
Why'd you message me?

25:47.937 --> 25:50.940
I didn't. My wife did.

25:50.940 --> 25:53.639
Her name's Laurie.
Laurie Lowell.

25:53.639 --> 25:55.684
She can't be here.

25:55.684 --> 25:58.948
Because she died
four years ago?

25:58.948 --> 26:00.950
She's not dead.

26:00.950 --> 26:02.561
Your father isn't either.

26:04.954 --> 26:06.129
Prove it.

26:06.129 --> 26:07.740
Not here.

26:10.220 --> 26:12.701
[Cellphone buzzes]

26:12.701 --> 26:14.442
I told you...

26:14.442 --> 26:16.183
What?

26:16.183 --> 26:18.098
What's your
favorite song?

26:18.098 --> 26:21.492
[Sighs] What?
I don't -- I don't have one.

26:21.492 --> 26:23.451
What about your dad?

26:23.451 --> 26:24.800
He liked Queen.

26:24.800 --> 26:26.236
You trying to figure
out his password?

26:26.236 --> 26:27.934
[Queen's "You're My Best Friend"
plays]

26:27.934 --> 26:29.544
♪ Ooh, you make me live

26:29.544 --> 26:30.806
♪ Whatever this world
can give to me ♪

26:30.806 --> 26:32.242
Nice hack.
What'd you do?

26:32.242 --> 26:33.809
Get in through
their environmental systems?

26:33.809 --> 26:36.943
♪ It's you, you're all I see

26:38.292 --> 26:41.948
♪ Ooh, you make me
live now, honey ♪

26:41.948 --> 26:44.777
♪ Ooh, you make me live

26:47.083 --> 26:52.045
♪ Oh, you're the best friend
that I ever had ♪

26:52.045 --> 26:55.483
♪ I've been with you
such a long time ♪

26:55.483 --> 26:58.704
♪ You're my sunshine,
and I want you to -- ♪

26:58.704 --> 27:00.706
[Music stops]

27:03.273 --> 27:05.362
Laurie worked for
a Wall Street hedge firm.

27:05.362 --> 27:06.799
Made them a lot of money.

27:06.799 --> 27:08.844
On her 31st birthday,

27:08.844 --> 27:11.281
they put her in charge
of the trading team.

27:11.281 --> 27:15.895
We were set upstate
to celebrate, when...

27:15.895 --> 27:19.159
Well, you can read about it
on your phone.

27:19.159 --> 27:23.032
When she was in a coma,
her boss approached me

27:23.032 --> 27:26.862
with an option
to save her life.

27:26.862 --> 27:28.385
Upload.

27:28.385 --> 27:30.126
Logorhythms did
the procedure,

27:30.126 --> 27:31.824
but it was
a bait and switch.

27:31.824 --> 27:35.436
First they lied to me
and told me that it didn't work.

27:35.436 --> 27:37.612
Then they kept her locked
in their servers

27:37.612 --> 27:39.658
right next
to the stock exchange,

27:39.658 --> 27:42.443
making money for
Shyer & Stern,

27:42.443 --> 27:45.533
until she found
a way to escape.

27:45.533 --> 27:48.971
[Cellphone buzzes]

27:50.799 --> 27:58.415
♪

27:58.415 --> 28:00.156
Laurie: Maddie?

28:00.156 --> 28:03.246
For a long time,
I thought I was alone.

28:03.246 --> 28:05.727
The only soul like me
in the world.

28:05.727 --> 28:07.773
But then I discovered your dad.

28:07.773 --> 28:11.385
I tried to break him out
of Logorhythms a few days ago.

28:11.385 --> 28:13.300
The DDoS attack?

28:13.300 --> 28:16.520
It didn't work, and now
tougher barriers are in place.

28:16.520 --> 28:18.479
In order for me
to reach your father now,

28:18.479 --> 28:20.089
you need to infiltrate
Logorhythms

28:20.089 --> 28:22.918
and patch me
in through a wireless branch.

28:22.918 --> 28:25.312
Infiltrate?
I can't infiltrate.

28:25.312 --> 28:27.270
You won't have a problem
getting in.

28:27.270 --> 28:28.881
Your mom is heading
there tomorrow.

28:28.881 --> 28:31.274
I've intercepted e-mails
from their legal team.

28:31.274 --> 28:32.711
They seem scared of her.

28:32.711 --> 28:36.062
She wants them
to delete Dad.

28:36.062 --> 28:38.629
You can't let that happen.
Take the bracelet from Cody.

28:38.629 --> 28:41.981
I had it 3-D printed,
just for you.

28:41.981 --> 28:43.373
What is it?

28:43.373 --> 28:45.332
Freedom.

28:52.252 --> 28:54.384
He's coming!
Get ready!

28:56.735 --> 28:58.214
M-My room's this way.

28:58.214 --> 29:00.739
Cary: Renee, it's
a simple question --

29:00.739 --> 29:02.566
how long can we survive

29:02.566 --> 29:04.917
if you keep spending
more than I make?

29:04.917 --> 29:07.397
For chrissake, it was a dress!
It was one dress!

29:07.397 --> 29:10.313
Do you want me to wait until
everything I have falls apart?

29:10.313 --> 29:13.012
Oh. I didn't hear you
come in.

29:13.012 --> 29:15.492
Mom, this is Hannah.

29:15.492 --> 29:17.756
We're working on
a school project together.

29:17.756 --> 29:19.975
Hannah.
So nice to meet you.

29:19.975 --> 29:21.150
You too.

29:21.150 --> 29:22.586
So that's
all you have to say?

29:22.586 --> 29:26.286
Honey, this is
Caspian's friend, Hannah.

29:26.286 --> 29:27.548
We're not done.

29:27.548 --> 29:29.593
Can we discuss
it later?

29:29.593 --> 29:31.117
Why?
Because of her?

29:32.379 --> 29:34.468
Um, maybe I should go.

29:35.774 --> 29:37.863
Cary, come on now,
please.

29:37.863 --> 29:40.474
Yeah, right.
Like he has a shot with that.

29:41.214 --> 29:43.129
Ah!

29:56.403 --> 29:57.970
Hannah, wait!

30:00.276 --> 30:02.148
You okay?

30:02.148 --> 30:04.019
I didn't mean
to push that hard.

30:04.019 --> 30:06.935
"That hard?"
That wasn't hard enough.

30:06.935 --> 30:09.068
Next time,
don't pull your punches.

30:09.068 --> 30:17.946
♪

30:17.946 --> 30:26.912
♪

30:26.912 --> 30:35.834
♪

30:43.145 --> 30:44.494
[Beep]

30:44.494 --> 30:45.844
Waxman: Ellen.

30:45.844 --> 30:48.411
I've spoken to Julius Pope.

30:48.411 --> 30:49.848
He's agreed to meet with you to

30:49.848 --> 30:53.068
discuss fulfilling
your request.

30:53.068 --> 30:55.114
Between us, I think he's gonna
do the right thing.

30:55.114 --> 30:57.551
You'll see.
He's -- He's a good man.

30:57.551 --> 31:00.119
He's even flying back from
overseas to meet you in person.

31:00.119 --> 31:02.948
I'll -- I'll arrange to have
you come to our offices.

31:02.948 --> 31:04.471
[Beep]

31:04.471 --> 31:06.560
I want to go with you.

31:07.735 --> 31:11.434
This is
a pretty adult meeting.

31:11.434 --> 31:13.436
I understand why you
couldn't tell me the truth

31:13.436 --> 31:14.960
about Dad earlier.

31:14.960 --> 31:17.136
You didn't want me
to get my hopes up.

31:17.136 --> 31:20.791
I get that. But now that
I know what happened...

31:20.791 --> 31:23.969
If you're going to
permanently put him to rest,

31:23.969 --> 31:25.492
I want to be there.

31:25.492 --> 31:27.407
I have to be there.

31:32.716 --> 31:34.849
[Engine revving]

31:34.849 --> 31:39.898
♪

31:39.898 --> 31:42.030
[Helicopter chuffing]

31:42.030 --> 31:50.996
♪

31:50.996 --> 31:59.961
♪

31:59.961 --> 32:08.883
♪

32:09.405 --> 32:11.233
Is this
the uplink to Norway?

32:11.233 --> 32:13.975
We're almost done
transferring him.

32:13.975 --> 32:16.238
And this will be
the entirety of his code?

32:16.238 --> 32:17.544
Everything we've
scanned of him?

32:17.544 --> 32:18.980
Yes.

32:18.980 --> 32:21.200
When it's done,
I'll bring it over.

32:21.200 --> 32:31.732
♪

32:31.732 --> 32:42.308
♪

32:42.308 --> 32:44.701
Stephen Holstrom.

32:44.701 --> 32:47.008
"Visionary".

32:47.008 --> 32:49.793
David always said
believe the hype.

32:54.842 --> 32:57.149
Here we go.

33:03.242 --> 33:05.635
Julius Pope.
Thanks for coming in.

33:05.635 --> 33:07.898
We actually met once,
at a function some years back.

33:07.898 --> 33:10.162
Ah. Forgive me.
We'll see.

33:11.380 --> 33:13.730
This is Deirdre Ryan,
our general counsel.

33:13.730 --> 33:15.776
And this is Ellen
and David's daughter, Madison,

33:15.776 --> 33:19.040
who I knew since
she was this big.

33:19.040 --> 33:20.433
Madison.

33:20.433 --> 33:23.175
Your Dad was one
of our brightest stars.

33:23.175 --> 33:25.525
Yep. You read to delete
what's left of him?

33:34.186 --> 33:37.841
Once we wipe these,
he'll be gone.

33:37.841 --> 33:39.408
We have
a facility on site.

33:39.408 --> 33:42.411
We sanitize the data,
then degauss the drive...

33:42.411 --> 33:43.934
But we're not gonna
do any of that.

33:43.934 --> 33:46.415
Right.
Wait, what?

33:46.937 --> 33:48.765
Your husband and his
work product

33:48.765 --> 33:50.941
are the property
of Logorhythms.

33:50.941 --> 33:54.510
As such, his code
is our intellectual property.

33:54.510 --> 33:59.124
I wanted you here today
so I can say this personally --

33:59.124 --> 34:01.387
David Kim is a valuable asset
for this company,

34:01.387 --> 34:03.128
and we're not
going to delete him.

34:03.128 --> 34:05.565
Now now, not ever.

34:08.046 --> 34:10.004
Julius, what the hell --

34:10.004 --> 34:11.440
Sit down, Pete.

34:11.440 --> 34:13.051
But you had me
make the transfer. Why --

34:13.051 --> 34:14.835
You do better work when
you think you're being truthful.

34:14.835 --> 34:17.751
Ms. Kim came here
because she knows you.

34:17.751 --> 34:20.493
Now she knows me.

34:20.493 --> 34:23.061
David signed power
of attorney over to me.

34:25.367 --> 34:26.847
I brought
the documents.

34:26.847 --> 34:28.631
Deirdre: You have power of
attorney over his body,

34:28.631 --> 34:30.155
not his mind.

34:30.155 --> 34:31.982
We would argue that legally,
there's a difference.

34:31.982 --> 34:33.810
You're welcome to try
and challenge that in court,

34:33.810 --> 34:36.074
but it'll be a long
and expensive process.

34:36.074 --> 34:37.597
Are you prepared
for that?

34:37.597 --> 34:40.469
Are you prepared for
everything out in the open?

34:40.469 --> 34:42.776
You want the world to know
you killed a man,

34:42.776 --> 34:45.039
then enslaved
what was left of him?

34:45.039 --> 34:46.867
The government
will come after you,

34:46.867 --> 34:48.390
not to mention
your competitors.

34:48.390 --> 34:51.263
And Lord knows what the church
will have to say.

34:51.263 --> 34:54.440
With what proof?
Some emojis from a chat log?

34:54.440 --> 34:56.137
You know what I have?

34:56.137 --> 34:58.444
A PR team that'll tell the press
about an unhinged widow

34:58.444 --> 35:01.099
